metadata.name: Chromatic Chaos #27
metadata.description:
Chromatic Chaos is a vibrant and abstract generative artwork inspired by the colorful and expressive style of the renowned artist Wassily Kandinsky. The artwork is composed of a chaotic and dynamic arrangement of lines, stars, and geometric shapes, all rendered in a bright and energetic color palette. The lines and shapes seem to overlap and intersect, creating a sense of depth and movement within the composition. The overall effect is one of organized chaos, with each element vying for attention within the vibrant and playful composition. Through its use of color and form, Chromatic Chaos captures the essence of Kandinsky's bold and innovative style, inviting the viewer to explore and interpret its abstract and dynamic composition.

However, AI still lacks human-like creativity, empathy, and intuition. Humans are better at understanding context, emotions, and social dynamics, which are crucial in many situations. Combining AI with human intelligence can result in a powerful synergy that leverages the strengths of both. For example, AI can assist humans in making complex decisions or handling repetitive tasks, while humans can provide context and nuance to AI-generated insights.

Overall, the combination of AI and human intelligence has the potential to lead to groundbreaking discoveries and advancements across multiple fields, making it a cool and exciting prospect for the future.

metadata.name: The Symphony of the Ether #32
metadata.description:
Once upon a time, in a digital realm called the Ether, there lived a group of circles and lines. These shapes were unlike any other, for they had the ability to generate art all on their own.

The circles were a vibrant and lively bunch, always spinning and dancing about, while the lines were more reserved, preferring to stay in place and hold their ground. Despite their differences, the circles and lines worked together seamlessly, creating beautiful and intricate compositions.

One day, the shapes decided to use a special library called RoughJS to add an element of randomness to their creations. With RoughJS, the circles and lines were able to create even more unique and varied works of art.

As the shapes continued to generate art, their compositions became more and more complex. They began to resemble musical notes, with the circles representing the round and flowing melody, and the lines representing the strong and steady beat.

The art that the circles and lines created was so beautiful and mesmerizing that it became known as the Ethernal Notes. And as the shapes continued to generate these ethereal compositions, they became a source of inspiration and joy for all who viewed them.

The end. ;)

In live mode click "s" to save image (2200 x 3030).

+---+
The Symphony of the Ether by __Reiji_c
+---+
Made with vanilla javascript + (roughjs MIT License (c) Preet Shihn)

metadata.name: CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE #534
metadata.description:
1 of 5 in CENTURY-XXX, Series 2
Edition of 1000

Tribute to Herbert W. Franke
“In Honor of the Dinosaur of Computer Art” 

Herbert W. Franke, a pioneer of computer art, passed away on July 16, 2022 at the age of 95. CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE is an homage to Franke’s MONDRIAN software developed for the Texas Instruments TI 99/4 home computer in 1979, and it’s a fundraiser to digitize his archive:

“Our goal is to raise 20,000 Euro so that ZKM Karlsruhe can digitize Herbert W. Franke’s 1,800 manuscripts and make them publicly available. If we raise more money, it will be donated to the Rütgers Foundation which supports children and young adults in Africa so that they can get access to and work with technology.” 

Each frame, a single “pixel” is added to the CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE image. When the software first loads, 100,000 frames are run in the background to start things off. Keep it running for hours or days to see it transform entirely — it’s an “infinite animation.”

metadata.name: Junina #6
metadata.description:
"Junina" is a tribute to the June popular festivities in Brazil, when the streets and house facades are decorated on many cities, mainly on the Northeast Region of the country. Small flags, paper balloons, and lamps are hung on public space creating a very special atmosphere and colorful landscapes. 

Plenty of forró (traditional music), bonfires, fireworks, typical food and drinks are part of these festivities that celebrate rural popular culture. The “Festas Juninas” (June festivities) have an important affective place in the imaginary of the Brazilian population. 

"Junina" continues the experimentations with code of my previous work "Monotipia". The challenge of creating graphic compositions with simple elements remains. Searching and trying to delve deeper into ways to play with the rhythm and subtleties of transparencies, colors, shapes and textures.

This project is also an homage to the painters who made the Brazilian June festivities as the theme of their works, especially Alfredo Volpi (1896-1988) and Alberto da Veiga Guignard (1896-1962), but also Anita Malfatti (1889-1964), Emiliano Di Cavalcanti (1897-1976), Heitor dos Prazeres (1898-1966), and many others.

---
Features:
-> 8 palettes (rarest = grayscale)
-> 9 compositions
-> Elements: 6 geometric shapes OR mixed element compositions
-> 5 canvas formats: 
-----> tall portrait (9:16)
-----> portrait (2:3)
-----> square (1:1)
-----> landscape (3:2)
-----> wide landscape (16:9) = rarest
-> Border colors: 
-----> soft
-----> dark
-----> deep gray
-----> soberest color from palette
-----> random color from palette (rarest)

* The names of the color palettes are words related to popular June festivals. The decision to use untranslated expressions was made because these words carry many poetic meanings in Portuguese. For example, "cinza" means "gray" but also "ash". A word that refers to both the color and to the residue that results from burning wood in bonfires.

---
To save the image as a png file, type:
[1] save at actual size 
[2] save with 2000px height
[3] save with 3000px height
[4] save with 4000px height
[5] save with 5000px height

Depending on the size option, the render time can be long.

---
Created with p5.js

---

https://marcelonada.redezero.org/
@marcelonada

metadata.description:
Inspired by Kazimir Malevich works, “Притяжение” features the connection between shapes, their positions and colours.
Although, as the work tries to develop further into a non-objective world, some real sceneries can still be associated with it.

——————
